The diet of an obese child: bridal brunch and dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 are overweight, with 9 percent of schoolchildren being overweight and 5 percent of children being obese.
Obese children, however, are often from families with unhealthy lifestyles, as recent research has shown.
It shows once again how important the environment and patterns around it are for healthy human development.
For example, weddings are half as common in families with obese children as in families with normal weight.
Fried fries were eaten the day before a research-related event called Obesity is no coincidence for more than 19 percent of obese people.
Obese families also have a low level of exercise, but this is true of most schoolchildren today - only 15 percent of children said their parents find time to exercise at least once a week.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was carried out at the end of last school year and involved almost 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic.
It was the second year of the Obesity is not a coincidence event sponsored by General Health Insurance and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 pupils from grades 4 to 8 have been involved in the project.
However, proper nutrition and adequate family mobility are among the factors that are causing a dramatic increase in the number of overweight or even obese children.
"For example, only half of the respondents said they ate five times a day on breakfast-snack-lunch-snack-dinner, which is a basic requirement for proper nutrition", says one survey.
No breakfast and no wedding night
Experts point out that relative details, such as a regular family breakfast, are also essential for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 percent of schoolchildren's families eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst part was finding that 10 percent of households didn't eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a proper daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that unhealthy fries are much more common in families with obese children.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonade every day (70 percent).
While more than 40 percent of the children surveyed regularly participated in sports, their parents had less than half - 15 percent.
Make your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed the children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to choose their own menu from the options offered, according to their taste and opinion.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 years are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition".
Their favorite foods include a lot of moist, meaty, and sweet foods.
"The high popularity of sweet lemonade is particularly alarming", the final survey report states.
For lunch, pasta won over the poultry.
But the children practically didn't want any snacks, and they're also low on fish and lunch vegetables.
Health Benefits
The study also showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they are given the right information.
"The control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the World Lecture on Obesity was not a coincidence, in a number of cases a significant shift in preference towards healthy eating", the results of the project stated.
This was especially notable for sweet lemonade, where more children began to prefer plain water.
Children also had far more frequently included poultry and fish in their questionnaires as their main meal of the day and restricted sweet foods and snacks.
