IBM's inventor is entering the second century of its existence.
If anyone were looking for the word that would most accurately express IBM's strategy, the closest thing would probably be "longevity".
To the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, a company that is seen as very modern, yet it's been a hundred years since its founding.
The foundation for this long-term vision was laid by the firm's first chief executive, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already issued a slogan that a number of world problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the imprint of the future giant's life (and also the name of an internal magazine that IBM started publishing in 1935).
It was also the foundation of Watson's carefully crafted corporate culture.
"For us at IBM, long-term thinking means continuous movement toward the future.
IBM survived and thrived for a hundred years because it remained true to its core values and was not afraid to change everything around it.
It allowed us to transform technology, business, and society during our first century.
We hope that we can achieve even more in the second hundred", said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current CEO.
The system developed
In the 1930s, Watson took care of his employees much like the businessman Bata in the Czech Republic - IBM employees were among the first American employees to have paid leave, employer insurance plus an elegant uniform and a sophisticated system to reward the best inventors and entrepreneurs.
IBM's long-term customer relationship is as sophisticated as it is.
The company was brilliant at bringing talent to the table from the beginning -- one of the first companies in the world to eliminate all discrimination so it could choose.
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan is for Palmisana to be succeeded as IBM's head next year by a woman, Virginia Rometty.
She's been with IBM for 30 years, still holding the position of head of sales, marketing and strategy.
IBM has been doing so-called online brainstorming in recent years, which has led to many future strategies and innovations.
No wonder there's plenty of ideas - almost half a million people work at the company.
Institutions with good reputation
A firm position in the business is secured by a firm's strong internal and external image.
"From the beginning, IBM had a concept of an institution rather than a technology company", said Harvard Business School professor of economics and author of the IBM book Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
"IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems through technology", added George Colony of Forrester Research, a consulting firm.
