How fares have changed since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were authorised in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time sold only tours to the countries of the Socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists have travelled to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (the Black Sea coast) and Hungary (Balaton).
A minor exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when travel to Yugoslavia was also possible, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned to the West and Czech tourists' travel to Yugoslavia was subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely individually, even within socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to, for example, Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation from that country, otherwise an individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered tours to the West, but it was necessary to stay up front overnight with a stroller or have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
But it wasn't won either.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czech currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a foreign exchange commitment, it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for a journey to the West.
By far, the Czech people spent the majority of their holidays in the country, which resulted in the large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs bought and this custom survives to this day.
The Czech travel industry has been undergoing a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
The enormous paradox that we no longer realize is that it was not possible for us to travel freely to Croatia, which is now the most popular country in the world, until 1989, when it was part of Yugoslavia.
As early as the late 1990's, visa requirements for neighbouring Western European countries were abolished, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna and Germany in Austria.
The Czechoslovaks couldn't afford to travel to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to see it for a while.
For example, in Paris, Czechs slept in tent parks because our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of travel in the Czech lands at this time was the carriage of their own food, cans, salads, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech crown, which allowed our tourists to finally freely buy Western currency for many tens of years.
But our standard of living and, with it, our average wages rose, leading to another milestone around 1997.
As a result of increased travel demand, travel agencies began to regularly prepare charter flights from 1997 onwards, making flights incredibly cheaper than in the past due to the possibility of booking quantitative discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs had visa-free access to virtually all developed countries in the world, except the United States, which continued to make travel easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel came in 2000, when, due to high demand, the first direct charter flight to the exotic world was made from the Czech Republic, to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists to warm distant countries are launched every year, and this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Today, exotic countries are visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States revoked Czech tourist visas, and our country was definitively ranked among the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50,3%) and for the first time in history spent more than CZK 15 thousand per person on a single holiday abroad, including the cost of stay.
