Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also a new vice-president of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we're talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite accurately, as "antihistorical work".
It contains several very well-known names, important contracts or famous battles, but it almost misses ambassadors, energy journalists, and discussions about tactics and equipment.
It is not a book about what happened, but rather, as the author explains, "a book about what it was like".
"Beauty and the Bold" combines the war experiences of 20 more and fewer men and women on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others will become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go insane or die.
Their lives are burning like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones being added to the web of destinies while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book is different from classic historical novels.
It corrects the notion that World War I was just a terrible trench warfare on the Western Front.
