Walls have eyes: How scientists are examining you on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man who was presenting his anti-immigrant views on the Internet.
On Monday, Braivik, who confessed to the July murderous outrage that left 77 dead in Norway, attended his first public hearing.
Although Breivik could have acted alone, he was definitely not alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time at the computer during the preparation of the attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social media sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, scientists want to know more about these people.
But how do we find them?
It's easy - just go to Facebook.
"We realized that getting them wasn't really that hard", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report by a British research team on European digital populism.
The amount of personal information on Facebook is so extensive, Bartlett says, that it was enough for scientists to simply use advertising on the site to pinpoint the demographic they were looking for with absolute accuracy - something that marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing fans across Europe, and they focused their attention and sent them ads, but instead of inviting them to join a new group or offering them some dietary products, they asked them to fill out a questionnaire that asked questions about their education level, their relationship to violence, and their optimism about their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without having to leave the office at all.
"It's a whole new way of doing research", notes Bartlett.
Some of the results are not surprising: online right-wing supporters are all young men who are encouraging the rising immigration rate.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who remain hidden behind a computer screen".
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and policy researchers use this site to study everything from health issues to social trends, including status updates, posts on walls, and clicked "I Like It".
Facebook reports over 800 million active users, each of whom provides on average three different data points per day, making it literally an "information supernova" that is behind a lot of new research.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it allows them to study people without having to bother them on the street.
"It used to be true that when you wanted to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"You have to get to a party where they'll never let you", Bartlett says.
"Facebook is breaking all this stuff down -- you just go straight to them".
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a social health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moren of the University of Wisconsin, a research team found that college students who discussed their drinking performance on Facebook were much more at risk of alcoholism than students who kept quiet about it.
Moren suggests that the peers of the site monitor and offer help to a student who publishes too many drunken statuses.
"A problem cannot be solved unless you can diagnose it", said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moren's book and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior, and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, Washington Post.
"We've found a way to identify vulnerable children that we otherwise would not have a chance to detect".
Facebook itself is constantly probing the data of its users.
The site's information team compiled statistics on the relationship between relationship status and Valentine's Day, voter turnout in 2010 and the national satisfaction coefficient (mostly using the information they had access to - Internet freedom advocates have long argued that the site should make its information treasure available to research and others).
But Facebook users know that they're being followed by a page, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the page needs to provide their personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don't even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules about how to collect data offline, but online data is accessible to everyone.
"I don't think most users thought scientists could look at their profiles", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study using his students' public Facebook walls.
"If it was about them, they took it as information between them and their friends".
The methodology question is also considered.
Even in offline research, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
There's no way to verify on Facebook how much of the information on the profile and the posts on the walls are true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things", Selwyn explains.
That is why Selwin, who has spent many years researching new technologies, believes that pencil and notebook are still the best tools for research.
"When you go out into the real world and talk to real people, it's something that can't be replaced", he says.
"Social research should be about society and social activities -- and a hell of a lot of social activities are still happening offline".
