Seven lessons from a lost interview with Steve Jobs in a movie coming out this week.
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, opinions began to emerge from people who compared him to Henry Ford -- and chose him for his genius as the greatest modern inventor.
In a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs, which was taped for a special movie coming out this week, for all Apple fans, it will be a fact that his creative mind perfectly understood the business processes and workflows behind his products.
He was an amazing designer, a dreamer, and a self-described member of the hippie movement, but also a pedantic organizer and a man who puts every little detail into the details - he believed that many entrepreneurs suffer "from the idea that a really great idea is 90 percent of their work... [but] there is still a long way to go between a great idea and a great product".
In 1995, Bob Cringely worked on the TV show Triumph of Computer Madness, which dealt with the dawn of personal computers.
By this time, it had been ten years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was busy with his new computer company NeXT, and he was eagerly awaiting the wide public's acceptance of the Internet.
The TV show ended up using only a short portion of Cringle's entire interview, and the original copies of the interview were traded as missing during transportation.
Shortly after Jobs' death, however, VHS copies were found in the director's garage.
It's this material, slightly cut, that forms the basis of a 68-minute video of Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which is heading to select theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who's famous for not being willing to give lengthy interviews, here Jobs seems surprisingly excited to talk about his technology philosophy and business strategies.
And he also shows himself to be a very thoughtful man.
Four times during an interview, there's a longer pause between question and answer -- 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, when you see Jobs perfectly think through the answer to make it as accurate and as accurate as possible.
There are times when Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, when he is impatient with Cringley's questions, and it drives him to get to more important issues and topics faster.
The interview was filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone, and it shows terrifyingly prophetic thoughts as Jobs evaluates what other companies are doing right and wrong, offering his own vision for the future of computing.
