The technological genius that has brought the company to its unshakable position is now being replaced by people who have no idea what good or bad products are - skill and technical knowledge are essential.
That's exactly what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have literally owned the entire computer industry.
It could be ten times bigger than it is, it could be a Microsoft of the '90s...
But instead of winning, they lost.
How he takes innovation as an art form:
"Between a great idea and a great product, there's a long way to go and a lot of work to do... and as that great idea evolves, it changes and grows".
You will learn a lot about him during that time.
You have to make a whole range of compromises - certain things you just can't force electrons, glass, robots or factories to do.
You have to keep 5,000 things in mind all the time -- different concepts -- and put them together...
And ultimately, it's all about taste -- you try to think about the best things that humanity has ever created, and in a way, you try to reflect them into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, but the best artists steal.
I've never been ashamed of stealing the best ideas.
The Macintosh was so amazing and successful because the people who worked at it were excellent musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, and, by the way, the best computer experts in the world.
