How to Recognize a Lie
A fresh look at recent newspaper headlines reveals how serious and pervasive lies and deceit are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy accusing several women of sexual harassment - both sides claiming the other is lying.
Penn State administrators were accused of perjury in trying to cover up records of a retired football coach sexually assaulting a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught on a microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
The lie has destroyed entire careers and sealed the stability of many countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitor Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by publishing information that was immediately disproved by undeniable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was accused of misusing campaign finance to try to cover up his unmarried affair.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that broke up with Bill Clinton when he lied about his sexual orientation with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in office.
There's stories of cheating all over the place, in school and at the university.
There are instances where teachers give their students test answers themselves just to make them look good in their assessments.
Mentors who should teach the reverse send a message that lying and deceit are acceptable.
How many scams are we facing?
Studies show you can get anywhere from 10 to 200 cases in a single day.
Suppose many of them are merciful lies.
Another study found that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of their first encounter.
Detecting lies, or "recognizing lies", is a necessary skill that anyone should acquire, whether for personal or professional reasons.
But it's not a social game that would be like, say, Sharad, where you shout, "I got you".
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars are looking you in the eye.
It's not like they're shaking, or cooking, or red-hot, or sewing.
But don't assume that liars are hard to spot and expose.
A trained lie detector can reveal the truth from the structure of the sentence, the small facial expressions, the way questions are asked and their timing.
I have spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from a vast and growing industry in the field of lie detection, and it is clear that lying is a modern skill that is easy to learn and can be very helpful in today's complex world - especially if your job responsibilities include hiring, conducting interviews, negotiating, or leading people.
Good liars can read well in others, let them be watered in alertness, direct their emotions, and intuitively realize how the other party is receiving them.
Research shows that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more "other-centered" lies - mostly to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie to their partners less often than single people (although the lies they tell are usually "horrible").
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of the subject.
It's called "initial observation".
It'll give him a lot of information to compare to later.
Notice the subject's body posture, his laughter, his voice work.
You should know if someone is typically constantly clapping their feet so that you do not unfairly accuse them of lying just because the meeting room is starting to clapping their feet.
Then try to identify the differences between false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
But take it only as a warning sign, not as proof of a lie.
Liars may stop moving their upper half of the body as they try to recall their fictitious story, they may shoot the tips of their shoes to the door, bend to the east, significantly alter their posture, or they may show "conversation relief" - exaggerated relaxation and change of position when confessing is difficult.
People who conduct interviews often give a false signal that the interview is over just to see what the relief will be like when it's over.
Also understand the language of the subject.
There's a famous story about how Scott Peterson once recanted and used the past tense to claim that his murdered wife was alive, which sparked a nationwide search for her body.
Lying individuals may also express themselves in a moderate way, "I had no sexual relations with that Mrs. ... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat the difficult question.
The most common verbal signs are very minor.
Some may use a lot of "softening language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... from what I know... to my best conscience".
Such a response will not reveal too much, and it is often another warning sign.
There is no magic that can expose every lie, but it is possible to learn the skills that can help detect lies.
These skills will help a person to avoid being exposed to some kind of liar and fraud in his personal and professional life.
