The Court approves the "end of analogue broadcasting" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court of the State (SCJN) rejected a constitutional action brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree that aims to speed up the so-called "deactivation of analog signals" and implement it in 2015 instead of 2021.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juana Silva Meza, believed that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued a decree setting out the individual steps that will lead to the transition to terrestrial digital television.
The Court of First Instance rejected the action brought by the Senate on the ground that the qualified majority of eight votes needed to give a ruling on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree in question was not reached.
The draft judgment drawn up by Minister Olgou Sánchez Cordero proposes the possibility of declaring the decree unconstitutional, since the regulation of all matters relating to radio and television is a matter which is reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofet), thus violating the principles of hierarchical subordination and the exceptions to the law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies supported a constitutional dispute in an attempt to fight against the decree.
The meeting of ministers also decided to reject the action brought by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the debate on the proposal, which is also the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the arguments of the proposal that the federal executive cannot structure measures to prepare public administration through general standards.
"I don't think even if she did that would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", he said, noting that public policy planning in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate to determine the direction of the state.
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the biggest changes the world has seen in recent years, with better use of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
He believes that delaying change would mean delaying the benefits of digitisation, which requires decisions in the public interest, since digitisation is not only of a technical dimension but also "concerns economic, social, political and national security issues".
He stressed that these issues "require the operation of the entire system in place, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State.
He recalled that a number of countries around the world had already completed the transition to digital, and through their governments, despite having highly specialized technical bodies at their disposal.
He stated that it was not possible for the government to introduce into the administration of the administration compliance with laws prepared by the legislature by issuing a non-conforming decree that interferes to some extent with the powers of Congress.
In Michoacán, they're analyzing the possibility of counting "voice by voice"
According to PREP data, the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is less than 27 percent.
The possibility of counting "voices by vote" appeared in this year's Michoacán election, where, according to data published by the Preliminary Election Result Programme (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is less than 27 percent, and 879 votes out of a total of 6074 constituencies have not yet been counted.
In this context, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the Electoral Authority approved a number of measures that should harmonise local standards with federal electoral reform.
As will be noted, Michoacán has not officially ratified its political constitution or its State Electoral Code or Electoral Justice Act, as the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force was due to expire in this election period, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel has denied their publication within the deadline set by the Official Gazette Act, saying he had any objections to them.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of the State (SCJN) resolved a constitutional dispute initiated by the local legislature and declared the vote of the Head of State on constitutional reforms to be "invalid and illegal" because he had no right "to approve or veto them".
When asked whether the counting could be carried out 'by voice', María de los Ángeles Llanderal replied that the approval of the relevant measures by the IEM General Council would allow the local electorate to carry out both the partial and the total counting.
In this way, a partial counting of votes, one or more ballots, will be possible under the following conditions: the results of the election are not agreed; there is no record of the counting and calculation in the relevant box or the President is not available; or if errors and obvious violations of the election results have occurred.
In addition, the total number of votes in all polling stations will be possible if there is evidence that the difference between the potential winner of the election and the candidate in second place is less than or equal to one percentage point; whenever an explicit request is made at the beginning of the session by the representative of the party and/or coalition that proposed the candidate in second place.
The total number of votes will also be possible if, after a proper count, the difference between the likely winner and the candidate in second place is found to be equal to or less than one percentage point and also if there is an explicit request from the political party whose candidate finished second.
It should be noted that in this situation there are elections in Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between first and second places is less than 0,16%, although 129 of the 923 electoral districts have not yet been counted.
