On Wednesday, a new Italian government will be appointed.
Prime Minister-elect Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face the crisis that is keeping this country above the brink of an economic catastrophe.
The Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with the Italian President tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face a crisis that has kept the country above the brink of an economic catastrophe and has put the entire eurozone at risk.
The Presidential Palace issued a report announcing that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgi Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to introduce a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti has announced that he will present the results of his talks with political parties to form a government to the president.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult stage", the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments suggested that obstacles were overcome.
"The frame is now well marked", he added.
Monti completed the government formation process in less than three days, much shorter than usual, while Italy struggles to cope with the political and financial crisis that has brought debt levels to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the tough package of austerity measures required by European leaders, only to restore Italy's broken credibility.
Monti is under a lot of pressure to move forward, and because of the volatility of the markets, the interest rates on Italian bonds, BTP, have exceeded the seven percent threshold for a decade, the level that Greece and Ireland had to apply for bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian employers' organization Confindustria, told reporters after meeting with Monte: "We said we would strongly support this government".
We believe this government is the last chance to get Italy out of this crippling situation.
Monti's hopes for success were greatly increased by the support of PDL leader Silvio Berlusconi, who resigned on Saturday after the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to bring good results", Angelina Alfano, the secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because up to this point, many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government of Monti.
Support for Parliament
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support to push unpopular austerity reforms.
Any obstacle or delay in the effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has joined the pressure, warning that Monti's failure could mean disaster.
Monti launched talks with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women's organisations on Monday.
The round of negotiations ends on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by President Napolitan, who made it possible to respond to the crisis very quickly.
After a brief decline from late last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian bond yields have returned to a critical threshold, reflecting uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will be successful.
To save Italy, whose public debt is EUR 1.8 trillion, would be beyond the possibilities of the current financial reserves of the euro area.
Monti stated that his government should remain in power until the next elections scheduled for 2013, despite general forecasts that politicians would only give him time to reform and then call early elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that this government must be composed of only experts to get Italy out of the trouble the country has been in due to financial pressure.
Political sources said that mutual distrust and disagreement between the parties complicate the attempt to integrate political figures into the government.
