The quintet included the country on its 20th anniversary tour.
"A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview for Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to play one of the best shows at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We've been waiting for over 20 years, but the band itself is making sure that the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true for them.
That's what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament said, speaking exclusively to Viva last week from Brazil.
The group is on a 20th anniversary tour of South America and will be at a unique stopover in Central America on Sunday.
He'll be performing at 7:30 p.m. at the National Stadium with the Angel Band The X and the National Musicians of Las Robertas.
This is a sample of an interview, a full transcript of which can be found on La Nación's website.
For your Costa Rican fans, it's a dream come true.
The journey to Costa Rica is also our dream come true.
We've barely been to South and Central America a second time, and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation, and it's a beautiful country, and I believe we can spend a few days here.
So we're very excited to bring you our music.
I'm asking, because the band is literally loved here, the fans are having these days of preparation very intensely.
What do you say to your most ardent supporters?
Thank you for staying with us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, and we thank you for waiting so long, and we're sorry it took us so long.
Some people already call the concert the biggest show of the year.
Does it put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we've done in the last 21 years have been set up in a matter of weeks.
We've done some great shows in Sao Paulo, and we hope that's how we get fit for a concert in Costa Rica.
We're really looking forward to the concert.
We love this country, we love surfing, we love the jungle, and for both of these things, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you know Costa Rica and its surf-friendly waves?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo.
My friends go surfing in Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico, and these are the best places to surf, and that's how we learned about Costa Rica, through people who love surfing.
Looking at your tour, you've put on a huge show with lots of songs.
What are you planning for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, we have no restrictions on what we can't do.
We're going to try to put on the best show with the best variety of songs, play a few songs from each album, and introduce our fans to a good, diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why? Why?
I think part of it's because we have nine albums and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to choose which songs we're going to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven't played in a long time, we focus on them and we're also surprised, because we remember why we liked them so much and maybe we've already forgotten about it.
So the show is more interesting to us, and that's why I think it's more interesting to people.
This tour is to celebrate 20 years of artistic excellence.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you've accomplished?
Yes, I'm sure you are.
First of all, I don't think either of us could have imagined that we'd be in a big rock band and stay in it for over 20 years.
We realize how much we've been given and we're thrilled to continue playing together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We're lucky to be able to look at the places we've always wanted.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were a significant part of the rise of the grunge genre?
It's always been an honor to be part of this group where the giants themselves are represented.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
Surprisingly, when a movement is born out of a group of friends, it doesn't happen very often.
From time to time, a group will be formed in a city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to come from one city at a time.
We're proud of that, and we're honored to be part of the Seattle team.
Sometimes we still play with some of them.
Last year we were at the Alice in Chains festival and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour, and we're lucky to have all of these friends, and we're honored to be part of this movement that started in Seattle.
It's also very unusual for a group like yours to stick together and have the same members over the years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which is itself a much longer time than the usual group life.
I think, first of all, we're all lucky to still be in this world, and secondly, we're always interested in each other.
We're all close friends, and that's what's allowed us to open up musical paths that give everyone enough freedom to experiment on their own.
We trust each other, we respect each other's music, and I think it couldn't be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been easy, but your success has allowed you to do whatever you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew older, it became easier and easier to find balance.
We try not to go on tour too much, because it's very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came here for music, you remember that you have to respect music and what you gave it, and you must not be carried away by being famous rock stars, which none of us have ever really cared about.
How do you remember the next project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote great songs, and at first it was something great.
We've been around for three years and we never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long, and most importantly, we still have friends today, Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started out in the band with us. And when I listen to a song or look at the photos, I remember Andy, how incredible he was, how I laughed at him.
She was an incredible person, and we miss her so much.
The national band Las Robertas will be commissioned to open a show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as the forerunners?
Yeah, the production sent us videos with a few suggestions, and we liked this group the most, so we're curious what Las Robertas are going to do live and they have to be really fun.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed, so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he adds the first thing he thinks of.
Who influences you as a bass player?
A lot of people.
The first to attack me is Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many of them I could talk about the bassists I like all night long.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge alive when it's not in style anymore?
I think we've all always felt a little bit separated from the word grunge.
When I talk about grunge, I think of the bands I mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came out around the same time, and if that's still the way music is today, that's great, because it's the kind of music that's worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are playing better music than ever before.
At first your music was a little cloudy, but now it's more positive.
What is behind this change?
That's interesting because I feel like there are a few songs on the new album that are easier to pick up, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very cloudy, even though they can sound positive.
Both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried, and they're deeply dark.
I think when you grow up and you have some trauma in your life, you lose someone from your family or friend, these things start to affect your art and your music, and these two songs are what they mean to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
