Fujimori was hospitalized again for medical tests.
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized in a public hospital on Tuesday, where he will be tested for muscle loss in his lower extremities, his attending physician said.
Fujimori, 72, serving a 25-year sentence for human rights violations committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has undergone four operations and is currently under medical supervision.
His personal physician, Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, told Canal N that Fujimori will be tested at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases in three days to determine why he is in pain and why he is losing his lower limb strength.
Aguinaga said he believed Fujimori could get mercy for humanitarian reasons, but the former president himself doesn't want mercy because he feels innocent.
He had four operations for tongue cancer, lost 18 pounds, and had other ailments, such as severe erosive gastritis, salivary cysts, kidney stones, high blood pressure, and circulatory problems in his legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been serving his sentence since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people killed by an illegal army squad in the early years of his rule.
