Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome has provided details of the plane crash that killed the governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven others.
The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) has informed that the results of the investigation into the accident in which Cabinet Secretary Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people died indicate that the helicopter crashed directly into the ground with full force, without the pilot having a chance to attempt a forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary for Communications and Transport, said that before the flight took off, the pilot had stated that climate conditions would allow flights.
"The parts that appear indicate that the unit has come into contact with the ground several times, wings intertwined with tree branches 25 metres from where the unit lost its hull".
It also informed that the unit was intended for 19 persons and therefore fulfilled all the requirements for the transport of personnel.
In addition, it stated that, based on the investigation carried out in the crash area, no components were found on the ground.
"The search found that parts of the aircraft were not located elsewhere, so the aircraft hit the mainland as if it were intact.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The terrain is sloping from 7 to 30 degrees.
The secretary assured me that at this time, it is most important to get results as quickly as possible, but the investigation may take months or even a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the crash, the President's General Staff helicopter was traveling at cruising speed and the accident occurred in soft upland terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that at the time of the accident it was a normal over-flight operation", he said.
At a press conference, SCT representative Pérez Jácome identified six key points of the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to visual flight rules, which means that the crew must be able to see the ground during the flight.
Weather conditions:
The AICM reports indicate the appropriate conditions of take-off, according to which the aircraft is moving towards the border, between DF and the State of Mexico were visible layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Routes selected:
It's likely that the crew was looking for a lower area and greater visibility into the Cuernavaca Valley because of the clouds.
Location of impact.
The impact coordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter are consistent, it is likely that there was no loss of control or disruption of flight path before the impact.
Dispersing of aircraft remnants in limited territory:
The information we have at this time allows us to assume that the impact occurred in a straight path and from the side.
The scatter pattern of the aircraft's remains suggests that the helicopter was intact at the time of the impact.
There was no fire or explosion.
No evidence was recorded at the scene of the accident indicating an explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During the fieldwork, the remains of the aircraft were found at an altitude of up to 9,200 feet above sea level, the terrain is sloping, the slope is between seven and 30 degrees.
The photographs show footage of the likely breakdown along the route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have come into contact with the ground in several locations.
After careful searching of the area around the accident, no helicopter remains were found in a territory larger than the designated area, which reinforces the assumption that the crash occurred while the helicopter was still intact.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has started research on the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance is conducting research to identify the gene responsible for childhood and adolescent obesity.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to uncover the genes that cause obesity in children and young people.
In a report, the head of the Biochemistry Medical Research Unit at the National Center for 21st Century Health's Specialized Hospital, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been set up.
This team is supported by postgraduate specialists and students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The public, whether or not authorised, can also participate in the research.People can come to the participating IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where tests will be carried out on juveniles every Saturday from 8 a.m.
He stressed that the research had started at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (Mexico State) and that since 8 October this activity has also been carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Centre (East Mexico State).
Once data on 500 to 600 children are collected, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Centre (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of the Federal Centre).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to track risk factors in Mexican children and young people and thus prevent the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim was to collect data from 3,000 children and young people aged between six and 14 years, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of inherited diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal failure.
He specified that every Saturday anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference) would be made to all participants, blood pressure measurements, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin levels, and gene studies (an attempt to identify genes that contribute to childhood obesity) would be made.
Cruz López said the research reflects healthcare professionals' concerns about the alarming increase in child weight.
'Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, only boys experienced a 77% and girls a 47% increase in obesity, and there was a dramatic increase in overweight too,' said an IMSS expert.
He said that one of the reasons for the search for indicators is the belief that the country's population differs from other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Native American genetic makeup, 30% European and 5% African, and that this is reflected in the genes responsible for diabetes and obesity.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity is commonly explained as the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of participants was that they were given an overall assessment of the children's condition, which would determine whether they were overweight or obese.
He noted that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm suggests the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and precancerous conditions.
The information is confidential, and doctors are writing it to parents explaining all the measures and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent their children from getting sick.
Cruz López explained that there are three main factors that cause overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: sedentary lifestyle that means a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the television all day long, and using transportation instead of walking short distances.
Overweight is also caused by high calorie intake, i.e. higher consumption of sweetened beverages, high fat, protein, high carbohydrate (tamask, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) and genetic stress, which is the subject of this research.
There will be no breakdowns in the asphalt from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalt with polymers to create a mixture that is more functional, regardless of climate and temperature.
If the pavement were properly maintained, almost 200 000 debris would not need to be repaired after each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who added that if the construction and maintenance of the asphalt pavements were adequate, there would be a significant reduction in debris, or even removal of debris.
In his talk on the Technological Cause of Scaffolding, delivered at the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that under his leadership, the laboratory would develop modified asphalt with polymers to produce a mixture with similar properties as asphalt but greater mechanical resistance at both low and high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, such as some cities in the north of the country, improving functionality and reducing the production of debris.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a group of hydrocarbon molecules, high molecular weight molecules called asphaltines, and other low molecular weight molecules called maltes, which together give asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost solid, while at low temperatures it tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but varies during the day depending on weather conditions and temperatures, warns a chemical engineer.
A scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible tile, made up of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the highest layers is the asphalt slab, made of small stones poured into the asphalt and then pressed.
He stressed that every stone that forms the insert is poured with asphalt.
When driving cars or creating pressure, it is possible to distribute the forces well in the carpet.
If it were modified asphalt, it would break down even better, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that the final layer of the asphalt slab is a layer called a mantle, made of fine stone, or sand, also poured into the asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with the vehicle racks, it must have greater mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and must ensure the friction of the road.
Since the coating will be subjected to a high load as part of the bearing, the coating must be of sufficient thickness and care must be taken to the material from which it is made.
Climate, particularly humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors to keep in mind.
Once the terrain is wet, the water spreads inward and is difficult to get out, it causes all the layers of the tile to soften and thus create wrinkles.
He explained that the film of the coat is first destroyed during the formation of the cracks and then the asphalt inserts are damaged, but the damage is not done at a moment's notice but is a slow process that should be stopped at the first seals by appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of wrinkles, and that the thickness of each individual tile layer must therefore match the load of the vehicle and ensure that this load is not exceeded.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that much work and research is still in the early stages of the asphalt project, including asphalt emulsions, which are already available in other countries and allow for easy repair of the abrasion without the need for high temperatures.
