Austria thus follows on from the request of the Eurozone Summit held in Brussels on 26 October 2011, where Heads of State or Government strongly requested that the reduction of the public deficit and the achievement of a balance of public accounts be incorporated into the Constitution or the Law of the same value by the end of 2012.
The instrument adopted by the Austrian government is close to the "German model", Germany being the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
The public structural deficit will have to decrease by 0,75% of gross domestic product (GDP) every year by 2017 and, from 2017, the federal government's public structural deficit will not be allowed to exceed 0,35% of GDP every year, while the federal countries and municipalities will have to report balanced budgets.
The objective is to bring the public debt below the 60% criterion set out in the Maastricht Treaty in 2020/21.
