Why is there such a high proportion of unemployed handicapped workers?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
Today is the 15th week of disability employment.
Despite the voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the proportion of unemployed persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the whole population.
Is that depressing?
"No", emphasizes Eric Blanchet, CEO of the Adapt Association, which organizes Employment Week for the Disabled.
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times higher".
"However, much remains to be done".
It should be noted that many obstacles remain for unemployed persons with disabilities before they enter the workforce.
This is the case for older people: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% do not have a degree and only 10,000 of the 2.3 million university students are handicapped.
And finally, long-term unemployment is very common: 53% for the disabled versus 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that make returning to work particularly difficult and which are at the heart of the problem, according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, which was set up in 1992 to help enterprises recruit handicapped workers.
So much for the objective brakes.
There are still unspeakable ways of thinking that are certainly developing, but too slowly.
A study by IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité in April found that managers surveyed had "a poor level of knowledge about disabled people" with "an overestimation of people in wheelchairs and mental or mental disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the target of employing 6% of handicapped workers set out in the 1987 Act.
The latest figures, which date back to 2008, show a level of 2,6%.
"We are now moving around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, which collects fees from companies that do not comply with the law.
The evidence is the number of 'fined' enterprises, as well as the amounts paid, which decreased between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law which increased contributions put a lot of pressure on businesses", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large businesses".
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
